In 1978, Shah as a twenty-five year old had traveled all the way to Ward 141 of Moscow as a courier, with the communications addressed to the district’s chief and delivered to sender. Instead of signing for the parcel, he went home with the package. This incident was of importance to him as he was taught to differentiate himself from other writers. It was also another stepping stone towards becoming a writer. He writes,

This was the decision that changed my life. Politics, history, the craft of writing were always fighting for my allegiance. I know that writers will rarely tell you this, but it is not easy to decide whether to become a novelist or journalist, to write biography or ode. When you choose one thing for the rest of your life, your career is finished in nine months. There is nowhere else to go, and your brain forms a pack square, assumes a formal position for the rest of your life. What’s interesting in my life is I’ve been able to do something anew every few years.
